==English==
===Etymology===
From Latinized {{Gr.}} ''sympathia'', from [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[συμπάθεια]]''' (''sympatheia'') "fellow-feeling, sympathy, affinity", from '''[[συμπαθέω]]''' (''sympatheo'') "to feel for, to sympathise", from prefix '''[[συμ-]]''' 
(''[[sym-]]''), variant of '''[[συν-]]''' 
(''[[syn-]]'') "with, in company with, together with" + '''[[παθέω]]''' (''patheo'') "to have a secondary affection", from '''[[πάσχω]]''' (''pascho'') "to receive an impression from without, to suffer"

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''sympathy''' (''plural:'' [[sympathies]])

#A [[mutual]] [[relationship]] between [[people]] or [[thing]]s such that they are [[correspondingly]] [[affected]] by any [[external]] [[action]], [[force]], etc.
#The [[abilty]] to [[share]] the [[feeling]]s of another; [[empathy]].
#A feeling of [[pity]] or [[sorrow]] for the [[suffering]] or [[distress]] of another; [[compassion]].

